WHAT IS THE PRINCIPLE OF CONSTRUCTIVE LIABILITY? DEFINE AND DIFFERENTIATE SECTION 34 AND SECTION 149 PPC RESPECTIVELY.



THE PRINCIPLE OF CONSTRUCTIVE LIABILITY.

Means-”if two or more persons do an illegal act or commit a crime together with common intention, they would be held liable for that act equally.”

COMMON INTENTION.

“it means the intention to commit a crime with mutual participation.”



SECTION 34 PPC.

When a criminal act is done by several persons in furtherance of the common intention of all, each of such persons is liable for that act in the same manner as if it were done by him alone. 

SECTION 149 PPC.

If an offence is committed by any member of an unlawful assembly in prosecution of the common object of that assembly, every person who, at the time of the committing of that offence, is a member of the same assembly is guilty of the offence.

ILLUSTRATION UNDER SECTION 34.

A, B, and C hit Z and finally C shoots Z. All three shall be liable for murder u/s 34 PPC.



6 X POINTS OF DEMARCATION BETWEEN SECTION 34 AND SECTION 149 PPC



NO. OF DIFFERENCES

WHEREAS

Under section 34 a criminal act is done by several persons in furtherance of common intention of all and each of such persons is liberal.  

under section 149 the offense may be committed by any member of unlawful assembly, in prosecution of their common object and every person is termed guilty for that offence. 



Several persons maybe two or more persons in number.

The number of unlawful assembly are always at least five in number one PPC on lawful assembly means assembly of five or more persons.

Under section 34, the criminal act is not an independent offense so having no punishment under PPC. It is ancillary to other offenses and may only be charged with them.

Under section 149 PPC the offense is an independent offense for which a separate charge is framed under a distinct head. However, it has the same punishment as that of the offense committed by five or more persons of unlawful assembly. 



Common intention usually cannot be developed on the spur of a moment. Mostly, it requires a prior meeting of mind.

A mob conspiring five or more persons maybe turned out to be an unlawful assembly if having the common object as defined under section 141 PPC.



Under section 34 PPC, there is criminal act so it may be regarded as less severe in itself.

Under section 149 there is an offense so it may be regarded as harsh.

Active participation of each person is necessary.

Active participation of each member is not required but it is sufficient to be a member of unlawful assembly to impose the joint liability upon all the members of such assembly.

