--- START OF FILE: Difference between Abetment 107-120 Vs Criminal Conspiracy 120A-120B.docx ---

POINTS OF DIFFERENCE BETWEEN:

ABETMENT U/S 107-120.

VS.

CRIMINAL CONSPIRACY U/S 120-A & 120-B.

HEADINGS

ABETMENT

CRIMINAL CONSPIRACY

Definition.

Abetment is defined under Section 107 PPC, as a situation where one person instigates, conspires with, or intentionally aids another person to commit an offence.   

Criminal conspiracy is defined under Section 120A PPC, as a situation where two or more person agree to commit an illegal act or a legal act by illegal means. 

Parties involved. 

In abetment, there are usually two parties involved: the abettor (the person who abets) and the principal offender (the person who commits the offence). 

In a criminal conspiracy, there are at least two parties involved known as conspirators. 

Nature of offence.

Abetment is not a substantive offence on its own. It requires the act of aiding, instigating, or conspiring to commit the offence. 

Criminal conspiracy is considered a substantive offence, where the mere agreement to commit an offence is punishable, even if the offence is not actually committed. 

Action for performance. 

In abetment, action for performance of an act is necessary. 

Criminal conspiracy does not require necessary action because conspiracy may be done by a verbal agreement only. 

Act or Omission. 

In abetment by conspiracy, there must be an act or illegal omission in pursuance of the conspiracy to commit the offence. 

In criminal conspiracy, the mere agreement between the conspirators is sufficient and no act is necessary to constitute the offence. 

Scope. 

Abetment has broader scope, encompassing instigation, conspiracy, or intentional aid. 

Criminal conspiracy is a specific form of abetment. 

Punishment. 

The punishment for an abettor may not be the same as that for the principal offender, depending on the nature of the abetment. 

In a Criminal conspiracy, all parties are liable to the same punishment as if they had committed the offence themselves.

