CONDITIONAL SENTENCES

THREE-CONDITIONS:

Conditional sentences starts with “Agar-If”;

They are formed in two parts;

At the end of each part “ga, gae, ge” like words come. 

NOTE 1:

If out of mentioned above three conditions even one condition is left out then the sentence will not be called a conditional sentence.  

NOTE 2:

Every sentence starting with ‘If’ does not have to interrogatory and all three conditions are necessary to be present. 

FORMULAE:

In Present Indefinite Tense 

Agar wale hisse ka tarjuma

Is in Future Indefinite Tense 

Jabke baqiya hisse ka tarjuma

NOTE 3:

In Interrogatory sentences it is better to start the sentence from the Future Indefinite Tense part. However, not necessary. 

NOTE 4:

Both parts are joined by THEN or COMA. 

Examples: 

ENGLISH TRANSLATED SENTENCE

URDU PHRASE

If you do your work in a befitting manner, you will win success.

Agar tum apna kaam zemadari se karoge tu imtian ma kamyab ho jao ge.

If you followed me, it would be in your benefit.

PAST TENSE

If you did your work in a befitting manner, you would win success.

PAST TENSE





