408: CRIMINAL BREACH OF TRUST BY CLERK OR SERVANT

Whoever, being a clerk or servant employed as a clerk or servant, and being in any manner entrusted in such capacity with property, or with any dominion over property, commits criminal breach of trust in respect of that property, shall be punished with imprisonment of either description for a term which may extend to 7 years, and shall also be liable to fine. 

Commentary

This section inflicts enhanced punishment on such a person for criminal breach of trust. The ingredients of the offence under S. 408 are: 

That the accuse was a clerk or servant etc.;

That he was entrusted with property, or with dominion over the property; and 

He had committed breach of trust in respect of such property.

The essential ingredient of S. 408 PPC is dishonest misappropriation. Prosecution to prove the entrustment of the property to the accused in the capacity of being a clerk or a servant or that he had dominion over the property; then to prove criminal breach of trust as provided in S. 406 of the Code. [PLD 1997 Kar. 311]

When the cash entrusted to the cashier of the bank had not been recovered from him or from his house and there is no evidence that he had taken that amount, though he was answerable for the amount as cashier, was not liable to be convicted U/s 408 Penal Code, as he had not dishonestly misappropriated the amount. [1998 Cri LJ 3771 (DB) (Bom)]

