. 5. | have heard learned counsel for the respect
through the material placed so far. I is indeed tre that iyiend ir
legal view favors the granting of bail in non-prohibitory offenses but
Honorable Superior Courts have equally emphasized that this rule is not ~~ |
absolute Discrebon may validly be exercised to refuse bail where
exceptional circumstances or compeling reasons are apparent on the
record. In the instant matter, this court is not merely concerned with the
statutory classification of the offense bul with the manner mindset and
context in which the alleged act was committed. The incident was not
accidental or momentary. The available video evidence, which is
uncontroverted at this stage, pnma facie demonstrates an organized and
deliberate act of aggression, involving multiple individuals who surrounded,
physically attacked and intimidated the victim in an overwhelming show of
force. More importantly, the status and influence of the primary accused
Muhammad Salman Farcoqi, cannot be ignored. At this preliminary stage, I
there are reasonable grounds to believe that accused Muhammad Salman
Faroogi along with co-accused, being influential individuals, may hinder or
manipulale the investigation, pressurize witnesses or tamper with
evidence, particularly with regard to those employees or bystanders who
may have been present but are yet 10 depose. It is trite law that where
there is real and not merely speculative fear of obstruction of justice, even
non-prohibitory offenses may warrant denial of bail. The judgments of the
Honorable Supreme Court of Pakistan in cases such as Muhammad Aizan
Arain Vs The State and Imtiaz Ahmed Vs The State (2008 SCMR 1784)
support the proposition that the accused's influence and possibility of
destroying or manipulating evidence is a valid ground for refusal of bail.
Although public sentiment alone cannot dictate judicial discretion but acts
of vigilantism (as happened in present case), especially by persons
